<title>The avoidance of the name of the lion</title>
<summary><i>The name of the Lion not to be spoken by children. In the Katkop dialect, by Día!kwãin, from ≠kámme-an (L V.-7. 4526 and 4526, 8. 4527-4562). Another version of this warning (L V.-8. 4563-4573).</i> The |xam avoid saying the lion&apos;s name so the flies cannot hear and report to the lion what they say; some of the lion&apos;s habits when killing game; what people must do when stealing game from a lion; they make signs or hand gestures to signify the lion instead of saying its name.</summary><comments>1) p.4525v: this story was &apos;taught&apos; to Dia!kwain by his mother (≠kamme-an), 2) p.4531v: a description of the hand gesture used to signify the lion (Dia!kwain made the gesture by way of illustration), 3) p.4544v: a note on a story told by a Mr Schreuder, 4), p.4558v: the lion is cunning; Dia!kwain&apos;s mother told him to cut quickly then leave the lion&apos;s &apos;killing place&apos;, 5) See also <i>The children taught to use another name for the lion</i>, 6) This story is found in Books V-7 and V-8</comments><date>5 April 1875 (started)</date><storypages>4526-4526 1/2, 4527-4562</storypages><category>Custom and daily life</category><category>Plants and animals</category><author>Dia!kwain (David Hoesar) (V)</author><keyword><kw>lion</kw><subkw>avoidance of its name</subkw></keyword>
